{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fb7161f5-2c77-4ab6-838d-9adf012f1a21","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n## 1. Tests Losing History in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **test-ID generation algorithm**. Azure DevOps tracks tests by ID, so they all appear \"new.\" To restore history, add this to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a **class-level context** — it has no associated test method. Accessing `TestName` throws `InvalidOperationException`. This is by design since class init runs once before *any* test.\n\n**Fix for your code (line 13):** Remove or guard the `TestName` access:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName instead, or\n    // move per-test logic to [TestInitialize]\n}\n```\n\n## 3. Other v4 Changes to Watch For\n\n| Area | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| **Parallel execution** | Now enabled by default at the method level. Add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.ClassLevel)]` or disable if tests aren't thread-safe. |\n| **`[DataRow]` display names** | Generated differently — may affect test filters/ADO tracking. |\n| **`[AssemblyInitialize]` context** | Same as ClassInitialize — no test-specific properties. |\n| **Timeout behavior** | `[Timeout]` now uses `CancellationToken` (cooperative) by default instead of thread-abort. Long-running tests must check the token. |\n| **`Assert.ThrowsException`** | Now validates exact exception type (not derived). Use `Assert.ThrowsExactly` or check inheritance yourself. |\n\nWould you like me to update your project files to fix either of these issues?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e10ec7c7-2fdd-473f-aafd-51a5ab05a5eb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user upgraded to MSTest v4 and is experiencing two issues:\n\n1. **Tests appearing as new in Azure DevOps** - This is because MSTest v4 changed the default test ID generation. In MSTest v3, the test ID was based on the test method's managed name. In MSTest v4, the default changed, which causes Azure DevOps to treat them as different/new tests (losing history).\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize] throws** - In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is no longer associated with a specific test. Accessing `TestName` on it throws because class initialization runs once before any test method, so there's no \"current test\" to report. This is a breaking change in v4.\n \nThese are the main v4 breaking changes to be aware of—the test ID computation shift and the class-level context no longer carrying test-specific metadata. There are configuration options available to restore the previous behavior if needed.\n\nBeyond those, I should also flag that accessing `TestName` in class initialization will throw an exception, and there are several other areas where behavior has shifted: how `[DataRow]` generates display names, potential changes to parallel execution defaults, `DeploymentItem` handling, the lifecycle of assembly and class initialization/cleanup methods, and how `TestContext.WriteLine` works in static contexts.","outputTokens":959,"requestId":"BC27:2BEA6E:22CCD39:26BE6E3:69FAAB51"},"id":"1e02b45b-0295-4396-a8bc-f7e281df0f99","timestamp":"2026-05-06T02:45:57.395Z","parentId":"2afc4b9f-cbc9-41c6-ba5a-6425b8264576"}
